Certainly! Below is a simple A-Frame web app that includes WASD navigation, 20 randomly colored flowers, brown dirt, a blue sky, and a white cloud that moves randomly in the sky. You can copy and paste this code into a single HTML file and open it in a web browser that supports WebVR.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <title>A-Frame Flower Garden</title>
    <script src="https://aframe.io/releases/1.2.0/aframe.min.js"></script>
    <style>
      body { margin: 0; }
      canvas { display: none; }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <a-scene>
      <!-- Sky -->
      <a-sky color="#87CEEB"></a-sky>

      <!-- Ground -->
      <a-plane position="0 0 -5" rotation="-90 0 0" width="100" height="100" color="#8B4513"></a-plane>

      <!-- Randomly placed flowers -->
      <script>
        const colors = ['#FF5733', '#33FF57', '#3357FF', '#F1C40F', '#8E44AD', '#E74C3C', '#3498DB', '#2ECC71', '#E67E22', '#1ABC9C'];
        for (let i = 0; i < 20; i++) {
          const flower = document.createElement('a-entity');
          flower.setAttribute('geometry', 'primitive: cylinder; height: 0.1; radius: 0.05');
          flower.setAttribute('material', `color: ${colors[Math.floor(Math.random() * colors.length)]}`);
          flower.setAttribute('position', `${(Math.random() - 0.5) * 20} 0 ${(Math.random() - 0.5) * 20}`);
          document.querySelector('a-scene').appendChild(flower);
        }
      </script>

      <!-- Cloud -->
      <a-entity id="cloud" geometry="primitive: sphere; radius: 1" material="color: white" position="0 5 -10"></a-entity>
    </a-scene>

    <script>
      // Cloud movement
      const cloud = document.getElementById('cloud');
      function moveCloud() {
        const x = (Math.random() - 0.5) * 20;
        const z = (Math.random() - 0.5) * 20;
        cloud.setAttribute('position', `${x} 5 ${z}`);
      }
      setInterval(moveCloud, 2000);
    </script>
  </body>
</html>
```

### Instructions:
1. Copy the code above.
2. Paste it into a text editor and save it with a `.html` extension (e.g., `flower_garden.html`).
3. Open the saved file in a web browser that supports A-Frame and WebVR (like Chrome or Firefox).
4. Use the WASD keys to navigate around the scene.

Enjoy your virtual flower garden!
